        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-11T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-11T23:00:00-05:00" n="448" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d448">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.50 Recovery/6–1248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-12T13:00:00+09:00">June 12, 1948—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 12—9:03 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1074. With respect to Lapham’s telegram to Hoffman and Moore sent from Shanghai
                    June 11 (number unknown<note n="1" xml:id="d448fn1">See telegram No. <hi rend="smallcaps">Toeca</hi> 31, <ref target="#pg_546">p.
                        546</ref>.</note>) recommending certain changes in draft bilateral foreign
                    aid program, Embassy fully concurs and recommends strong effort to employ
                    language proposed. If Chinese resistance too strong, particular in view lateness
                    of its introduction, then at least we could endeavor obtain Chinese oral
                    agreement on these points.</p>
                <p>Sent Department as 1074, repeated Shanghai 478.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
